There is an instance named xfusion-ec2 and an elastic-ip named xfusion-ec2-eip in us-east-1 region. Attach the xfusion-ec2-eip elastic-ip to the xfusion-ec2 instance.

Steps Using AWS Console:
1. Login to AWS Console:
Go to the AWS Management Console.
Log in with your credentials.
2. Navigate to EC2 Service:
In the search bar at the top, type EC2 and select EC2 from the list of services.
3. Locate the Elastic IP:
In the left sidebar under Network & Security, click on Elastic IPs.
Find the Elastic IP (xfusion-ec2-eip) from the list.
4. Associate the Elastic IP with the EC2 Instance:
Select the xfusion-ec2-eip Elastic IP.
Click on the Actions dropdown, then select Associate Elastic IP address.
5. Associate with the EC2 Instance:
In the Associate Elastic IP address window:
Instance: Select the EC2 instance xfusion-ec2 from the dropdown.
Private IP: Select the private IP associated with the instance (usually the default private IP).
Leave the Reassociation option unchecked unless you are reassigning an existing Elastic IP.
Click Associate to associate the Elastic IP with the instance.

Steps Using AWS CLI:
1. Associate the Elastic IP with the EC2 Instance:
To associate the Elastic IP xfusion-ec2-eip with the EC2 instance xfusion-ec2, use the following AWS CLI command:
aws ec2 associate-address --instance-id i-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx --allocation-id eipalloc-xxxxxxxx --region us-east-1

2. Verify the Association:
To verify that the Elastic IP was successfully associated with the EC2 instance, run the following command:

aws ec2 describe-addresses --region us-east-1 --allocation-ids eipalloc-xxxxxxxx
